title: sekiguchi_hiroshi_no_tokyo_friend_park_ii
body:
"Tokyo Friend Park 2 (Japanese: 東京フレンドパークII; often abbreviated as "TFP2") is a Japanese game show that premiered in April 1994 on the Tokyo Broadcasting System ([[TBS]]). TFP2 airs on Monday nights roughly from 6:55 - 7:54 JST in Japan." [1]

h4. Darts

"At the end of each show, participants can choose between taking the coins (worth ¥100,000 each) or trading their coins in for darts; most contestants trade their coins for a dart each. Participants will then throw their darts at a large spinning dart-board. ... Prizes range from a high variety of electronics to a [new car].  If the contestant's dart lands in the gray center circle, or in one of the gray sections around the outside, the contestant will win a tawashi (a sponge, the show's joke prize). If the thrown dart misses the board and lands somewhere else (like the background or the floor), the participant's name will be written on the place it landed." [1]

When a contestant is readying to throw the dart, the crowd chants "Pajero". The "Mitsubishi Pajero":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mitsubishi_Pajero] (known as the Montero or Shogun in some parts of the world) is an SUV that has traditionally been the top prize on the show. 

For an example of the darts segment, see "here":[https://vimeo.com/143764255] at 46m20s.

title: akai_koudan_zillion
body:
[b]Akai Koudan Zillion[/b] (赤い光弾ジリオン, lit. [i][b]Red Photon Zillion[/b][/i] in Japan), known elsewhere simply as [b][i]Zillion[/i][/b], is a [[1987]] [[science fiction]] anime series that originally ran from April 12, 1987 to December 13, 1987 on [[nippon_tv|Nippon Television]] and was produced by [[Tatsunoko Pro]]ductions, with promotional material published by [[Movic]]. 

After the production of the anime, Tatsunoko Production and Ishikawa Mitsuhisa, the producer of Zillion, established IG Tatsunoko (which later became [[Production I.G]]) to obstruct the dispersing of the excellent staffs of Tatsunoko branch which had done actual production. Therefore, Zillion is considered to be Production I.G's first work.

The anime was adapted into a [[Sega Master System]] [[video game]] called [i][b]Zillion[/b][/i]. This is an original space adventure platform video game developed by [[SEGA]] and designed for the Master System as a companion tie-in for Tatsunoko Production's Zillion anime series in 1987.

The Zillion series prominently features Sega's egg-shaped mascot, [[Opa-Opa]], who stars in the [[Fantasy Zone]] games, which are also available for the Master System. The main [[energy gun]] weapon of the anime is based on the design for the [[SEGA Light Phaser]] attachment for the [[game console]].

A sequel to the game, [i][b]Zillion II[/b][/i] was released in 1988.

title: keith_haring
body:
Keith Allen Haring (May 4, 1958 – February 16, 1990) was an American artist whose pop art emerged from the New York City graffiti subculture of the 1980s. His animated imagery has "become a widely recognized visual language". Much of his work includes sexual allusions that turned into social activism by using the images to advocate for safe sex and AIDS awareness. In addition to solo gallery exhibitions, he participated in renowned national and international group shows such as documenta in Kassel, the Whitney Biennial in New York, the São Paulo Biennial, and the Venice Biennale. The Whitney Museum held a retrospective of his art in 1997.

Notable work:
Keith Haring Mural (1984)
Crack is Wack (1986)
Tower (1987)
Todos Juntos Podemos Parar el SIDA (1989)
Tuttomondo (1989)

title: astaroth_(housamo)
body:
[[Tokyo Afterschool Summoners]] character.

His Sacred Artifact is a golden Snake that can perceive both past and future. Those afflicted by this serpent's venom will have their most deeply hidden memories exposed. Though only in speculation, there are some who consider these memories to be crimes one has committed in a past life or else future crimes yet to be committed. The memories that can be exposed include those regarding events beyond the 23 worlds connected to Tokyo. This is because powerful bonds between those who desire one another can cross even the wall that divides the worlds. It is said that if Astaroth himself is bitten, a woman with long, flowing hair that shines like the stars above will appear. In this Tokyo, one's Shadow and their original self are considered to be two separate entities, but in Astaroth's case, this is not entirely true. For to Astaroth, one's past life and future self are, in many ways, connected.

title: nagoya_(city)
body:
One of [[Japan]]'s major cities. The capital of [[Aichi Prefecture]] and the largest city in the Chubu region.

Home to the Atsuta Shrine (where the Kusanagi sword, one of the three Imperial Regalia of Japan, is housed), [[Nagoya Castle]] (where Oda Nobunaga was born according to legend in 1534), and Nakamura Park (where Toyotomi Hideyoshi was born in 1537).

title: nara_(city)
body:
The capital of Nara Prefecture in the Kansai region.
Nara was the capital of Japan during the Nara period from 710 to 794 as the seat of the Emperor before the capital was moved to Kyoto. Nara is home to eight temples and ruins that comprise a UNESCO World Heritage Site collective listing: [i]Historic Monuments of Ancient Nara[/i].

title: metal_gear_rex
body:
Metal Gear Rex is a mecha which appears in [[Metal Gear Solid]] and [spoiler]Metal Gear Solid 4 as a pilotable mecha[/spoiler].

Designed by [[Hal Emmerich]], it is armed with 30 Gatling cannon, anti-tank missiles, laser cannons and a large railgun [spoiler]which fires a projectile that is undetectable by any current ballistic missile detection systems and has an armor piercing warhead to penetrate bunkers[/spoiler]. Even though it is invulnerable to conventional attacks, its large radome is vulnerable to missile attacks.

In Metal Gear Solid, [spoiler][[Solid Snake]] is tricked by [[Liquid Snake]] to activate it[/spoiler], resulting in Solid Snake having to destroy it. After a battle, it was abandoned in the underground maintenance base. 

In Metal Gear Solid 4, [spoiler]Rex's railgun is removed prior to Solid Snake's (now known as [[Old Snake]]) arrival in Shadow Moses island. Solid Snake pilots it and engages [[Metal Gear RAY]], the Metal Gear designed to counter it, in battle outside the base. Due to the "Street Fighter" software control program which Hal Emmerich has secretly installed on Metal Gear Rex, Metal Gear won the battle and is abandoned after that[/spoiler].

title: last_man_battalion
body:
The [b]Last Man Battalion[/b], also known as the [b]LMB[/b], is one of four enemy factions from the videogame [[Tom Clancy's The Division]].

A Private Military Company composed of elite soldiers and operatives from the US Army's elite 75th Ranger Regiment and the CIA's Special Operations Group, they were hired by Wall Street business men to protect their assets in New York during the Green Poison outbreak. The LMB were at first allied with the Joint Task Force into bringing order in New York during the outbreak. However, the LMB's leader, Charles Bliss, began to view the JTF as weak in maintaining order as he and his men felt resentment for being abandoned during the outbreak. 

Eventually, Bliss and the LMB went rogue and aim to put New York City under their fascist, totalitarian rule where only the strong survive. Due to their military training and equipment, the LMB are the toughest enemies the Division face.

The LMB are usually seen with Winter Military uniforms and red armbands with a animal skull logo on it.

title: project_phoenix
body:
[b]Project Phoenix[/b] is an indie game being developed by [i]Creative Intelligence Arts[/i]. A squad-based real-time strategy video game combined with strong Japanese role-playing game design influence, the project is being described as [[Kickstarter]]'s first [[Japan]]-based video game project. The development team, self-described as "featuring AAA talent", includes [[Final Fantasy]] composer Uematsu Nobuo, and Arai Kiyoshi, an artist for [[Final Fantasy XII]] and [[Final Fantasy XIV|XIV]]. Violinist Yura Hiroaki will serve as the game's director and producer, while [[L.A. Noire]] QA analyst Vaughan Smith will be the game and battle designer.

The game's Kickstarter project successfully raised $1,014,600 (of $100,000 goal) on September 11, 2013; however, the project has since gone down as a disaster.
